idth: 641px) and (max-width: 1024px)"/><source srcSet="https://assets.replocdn.com/projects/fdd5614c-e48f-4183-abe2-06ecde4315b2/fe5bb4f2-dcb5-41bd-99c0-859ae538d3c4?width=1800" media="(min-width: 1025px) and (max-width: 2400px)"/><img src="https://assets.replocdn.com/projects/fdd5614c-e48f-4183-abe2-06ecde4315b2/fe5bb4f2-dcb5-41bd-99c0-859ae538d3c4" class="r-5se4ou" loading="eager"/></picture><div data-rid="f5ea967f-5af1-44e8-96ac-6fcc1bdc0da7" class="r-1qcjxpl"><div data-rid="0ad425c0-5e9f-4bc0-adb2-1de974fa4e9d" class="r-1hpq5ih alchemy-rte"><span style="width:100%"><h2>3. Stress Affects Young Chicks More Than Adults</h2></span></div><div data-rid="b87c52c8-a79e-4b3d-96ab-44f8782ffed6" class="r-tcyd0k alchemy-rte"><span style="width:100%"><p>Small changes can feel big to a baby chick. Moving from a brooder to a coop, changes in temperature, or meeting new flock mates can all create stress. Stress may affect appetite and digestion. Daily nutritional support helps maintain gut balance during normal environmental changes so chicks can adjust more smoothly.</p></span></div></div></div><div data-rid="cc03a538-7910-42d9-b6dc-7770975634ca" class="r-14ero19"><div data-rid="55922ea6-53a5-41dd-8cc3-403295fb71bb" class="r-55d4ac"><div data-rid="6b06ea22-0c87-4be1-b801-ea1cf0e6392e" class="r-voqim0 alchemy-rte"><span style="width:100%"><h3>4. Early Nutrition Builds a Strong Foundation</h3></span></div><div data-rid="5397c979-84af-4e7a-8005-fcf073d14d38" class="r-jbnfmg alchemy-rte"><span style="width:100%"><p>The first few weeks of life help build the foundation for strong bones, healthy feathers, and future egg laying. Vitamins and minerals play an important role during this stage. Adding daily support to drinking water helps ensure chicks receive balanced nutrients as they grow. A strong start leads to stronger hens later on.</p></span></div><div data-rid="ed7f9b62-ced8-42e8-afee-41ff2e8bdef3" class="r-9ncfsd"><picture data-rid="ed664268-ef5f-4a38-9ff2-35525380be67" class=